# Writing style

<!-- BEGIN: shared writing-style (synced from clause-dev/.shared/writing-style-fragment.md — do not edit in place) -->
## Tone

Low-ego, factual, expert-to-expert. No marketing speak, no hype, no cheerleading. Describe what it does, not how great it is.

## Top of document

The first three or four sections or paragraphs are prose that frames the piece. Lists, feature dumps, bulleted TLDRs, and similar structural content come after the framing. A document that opens with a flat bulleted list reads as a TLDR dump, not a considered piece.

Exceptions allowed at the top:

- Round-artifact metadata (`**Date:** / **Phase:** / **Scope:** / **Source topics:**`) inside `mock/design_rounds/` files.
- Tables with at least two columns and at least three rows of real content. Parallel-column information belongs in parallel-column form; single-column or two-row "tables" are prose wearing a costume.
- Table of Contents. If a TOC exists, it must be section one or two, never buried lower.

## Punctuation

**Em-dashes (`—`) are forbidden.** Not "sparingly", not "rarely", not "where nothing else fits". Zero em-dashes in any written content: prose, doc comments, commit messages, changelog entries, rule templates, anything. No real human writing for other humans reaches for the em-dash key; the people who do are either academic-writing stylists or shit-posting on the internet, neither of which is the register this work operates in. The em-dash interrupts a reader's rhythm and signals "look at me, I'm punctuating cleverly" when the underlying sentence would have read fine with ordinary marks.

Use one of the alternatives instead, always:

- **Period.** Break the sentence. Two short sentences almost always beat one long sentence bridged by an em-dash. When in doubt, pick the period.
- **Comma,** if the aside is brief and tightly bound to the clause before it.
- **Parentheses** (when the aside is genuinely parenthetical and removable without loss).
- **Colon:** if the second clause explains or expands what the first declares.
- **Semicolon;** if two independent clauses are so tightly coupled they belong in one sentence. Use sparingly; when in doubt, period.

Hyphens (`-`) are fine for compound modifiers (`fixed-point`, `lifetime-tied`, `zero-copy`). Do not conflate them with em-dashes.

En-dashes (`–`) are also forbidden in body text. Use "to" or "through" for ranges in prose (`lines 5 to 12`, `arities zero through eight`); en-dash is acceptable only in typeset numeric ranges where the style is established (rare).

No exclamation marks in prose. Public documentation is not a sales pitch and not a chat message.

Colons introduce lists, quotes, or clarifying phrases. They do not act as mid-sentence separators replacing a comma or period.

## Word choice

No hype words: "blazing", "seamless", "powerful", "amazing", "incredible", "game-changing", "best-in-class".

No corporate jargon: "leverage" becomes "use", "utilize" becomes "use", "unlock" becomes "enable" or the specific action, "streamline" becomes a description of what was removed. "Synergy", "holistic", "paradigm", "robust", "scalable" as loose adjectives: cut or replace with a verifiable claim.

No greeting openers: "Sure!", "Happy to help!", "Let me explain". Public docs are read by someone with a goal; state the first fact.

No filler: "it should be noted that", "essentially", "basically", "at the end of the day", "for all intents and purposes".

## ASCII diagrams

No hand-drawn ASCII box-and-arrow graphs, tree diagrams, or flow charts in prose. The effort-to-signal ratio is terrible: they take real time to align, they break under any font change or copy-paste, and they signal "I had free time to spare" rather than conveying information the reader could not have gotten from prose. The same content in a short paragraph, a nested bullet list, or a two-column table reads faster and stays correct when the underlying shape changes.

Allowed when the shape itself is the content and prose cannot carry it: a Mermaid code fence for a real graph (GitHub renders these), a short UML fence where the tool chain renders it, or an actual rendered image committed alongside the doc. A sequence of boxed nodes connected by `|` and `↑` in a fenced block is not one of these cases; rewrite as prose or as a hierarchical list.

```markdown
<!-- Bad: ASCII stack graph -->
notko  (zero deps)
  ↑
  ├── arvo
  │     ↑
  │     └── clause-*

<!-- Good: nested list -->
- `notko` (zero deps)
  - `arvo` (depends on `notko`)
    - `clause-*` (depends on `arvo`, `notko`)

<!-- Good: prose -->
`notko` has no dependencies. `arvo` builds on `notko`. The `clause-*` crates build on both.
```

## Emoji

None in public prose. Only exception: semantic UI mocks or diagrams where an emoji carries information a word cannot.

## Lists

Good for hierarchical content, genuine enumeration, and ordered steps. Long-form bullets with real content are fine; a bullet with three sentences is a structured paragraph.

Forbidden everywhere: bullets of the form `- <label>: <short description>`. The label-plus-colon form is cheat-sheet, not writing. Use a glossary table or prose instead.

Forbidden at the top of a document: flat single-line bulleted lists without hierarchy. (Exceptions above apply.)

Prefer ordered lists when order matters, unordered otherwise.

## Doc comments and inline comments (Rust)

`///` for items, `//!` for modules. First line is a brief summary under about 80 characters, because it renders into rustdoc index pages. Empty line, then details.

Inline comments explain why, not what; the code already tells the reader what.

Em-dashes are banned in doc comments and inline comments just as strictly as in prose. Replace with periods, commas, parentheses, colons, or a full rewrite.

```rust
/// A resolved handle to a registered entry.
///
/// Handles are resolved once at construction and reused across
/// lookups.
pub struct Handle { /* ... */ }

// offset because the catalogue is 0-indexed but display is 1-indexed
let display_idx = idx + 1;
```

## Error messages

State the problem and the fix. Name the types, values, and operations involved. Name the remediation.

```rust
// Bad
Error: width out of range

// Good
Error: UFixed<{I}, {F}> with S = Hot requires I + F <= 64 (Hot
container is u64 max). Use S = Warm or Precise for wider logical
width.
```

## Headings

Title Case for the top-level `#` (document title). Sentence case for `##` and below. Imperative or nominal, not interrogative.

## Commit messages

Format: `type: lowercase imperative message`. Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `docs`, `test`, `chore`. Breaking: `feat!:` / `refactor!:`. No parentheses, no capitals, no trailing period. Under 72 characters for the subject line. Body optional; explain why, not what. No em-dashes in the subject or the body.

## Enforcement scope

Rules apply to every piece of written content in the repo. The difference is automation, not standard.

Public-facing docs are gated at commit and push: `mock/PRINCIPLES.md.tmpl`, `mock/DESIGN.md.tmpl`, `mock/WORKFLOW.md.tmpl`, `README.md`, `mock/crates/**/*.md.tmpl`, `mock/agent/**/*.md.tmpl`, Rust doc and inline comments under `crates/**/*.rs`. The gate flags any em-dash occurrence, leading-paragraph lists, hype words, exclamation marks in prose, and the banned jargon. Em-dash detection is a hard block: any occurrence is a violation; prior "sparingly" framing is retired.

Round artifacts under `mock/design_rounds/` and research notes follow the same rules as a matter of discipline but are not gated.
